description.text: Specifies the parent node/object handle on which the rsvp configuration should be configured. In case modes modify/delete/disable/enable this denotes the object node handle on which the action needs to be performed. The handle value syntax is dependent on the vendor.

This argument determines if individual interface, session or router handles are returned by the current command. This applies only to the command on which it is specified. Setting this to 0 means that only NGPF-specific protocol stack handles will be returned. This will significantly decrease the size of command results and speed up script execution. The default is 0, meaning only protocol stack handles will be returned.
The number of RsvpLsp to configure on the targeted Ixia interface. The range is 0-1000.
MAC address to be used for the first session.
Valid only for -mode create. The incrementing step for the MAC address configured on the dirrectly connected interfaces. Valid only when IxNetwork Tcl API is used.

Enables vlan on the directly connected ISIS router interface. Valid options are: 0 - disable, 1 - enable. This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is an ISIS router handle.
For multiple neighbor configuration, configures the VLAN ID mode.

Valid only for -mode create. Defines the step for the VLAN ID when the VLAN ID mode is increment. When vlan_id_step causes the vlan_id value to exceed its maximum value the increment will be done modulo <number of possible vlan ids>. Examples: vlan_id = 4094; vlan_id_step = 2 -> new vlan_id value = 0 vlan_id = 4095; vlan_id_step = 11 -> new vlan_id value = 10
VLAN user priority assigned to protocol interface.

Interface IP address of the RSVP session router. Mandatory when -mode is create. When using IxTclNetwork (new API) this parameter can be omitted if -interface_handle is used. For IxTclProtocol (old API), when -mode is modify and one of the layer 2-3 parameters (-intf_ip_addr, -gateway_ip_addr, -loopback_ip_addr, etc) needs to be modified, the emulation_ldp_config command must be provided with the entire list of layer 2-3 parameters. Otherwise they will be set to their default values.
Define interface IP address for multiple sessions. Valid only for -mode create.
Gives the gateway IP address for the protocol interface that will be created for use by the simulated routers.
Valid only for -mode create. Gives the step for the gateway IP address.

The IP address of the unconnected protocol interface that will be created behind the intf_ip_addr interface. The loopback(unconnected) interface is the one that will be used for RSVP emulation. This type of interface is needed when creating extended Martini sessions.
Valid only for -mode create. The incrementing step for the loopback_ip_addr parameter.
Number of P2P Ingress LSPs configured per IPv4 Loopback
Enable to configure P2P Egress LSPs
Do Make Before Break on Apply Changes
This specifies the Backup LSP session Id. The default value is 30000. The minimum value is 0 and the maximum value is 65535.
Number of P2MP Ingress LSPs configured per IPv4 Loopback
Number of P2MP Egress Tunnels configured per IPv4 Loopback
P2MP ID displayed in Integer format
P2MP ID displayed in IP Address format
P2MP ID displayed in Integer format
P2MP ID displayed in IP Address format
Number of P2MP Ingress Sub LSPs configured per RSVP-TE P2MP Ingress LSP
This is used for generating the traffic for those LSPs from PCE for which the Symbolic Path Name is configured and matches the value.
Activate/Deactivate RSVP-TE PCEP Expected Initiated LSPs
Number of Expected PCE Initiated RSVP-TE LSPs
The period of time a PCC waits for, when a PCEP session is terminated, before revoking LSP delegation to a PCE and attempting to redelegate LSPs associated with the terminated PCEP session to PCE.
The mode of LSP in which it is currently behaving.
If selected, BFD MPLS is enabled.
If set to True, LSP Ping is enabled for learned LSPs.
Indicates whether Association will be included in a RSVP Sync LSP. All other attributes in sub-tab-PPAG would be editable only if this checkbox is enabled.
The Association ID of this LSP.
Indicates whether Protection LSP Bit is On.
Indicates whether Standby LSP Bit is On.
If set to True, LSP Self Ping is turned on for RSVP Ingress.
This specifies the session Id of the LSP Self Ping. The default value is 1. The minimum value is 1 and the maximum value is 2^64-1.
This specifies the IP header TTL of the Self Ping packet. The default value is 255. The minimum value is 1 and the maximum value is 255.
This specifies the IP header DSCP of the Self Ping packet. The default value is 48. The minimum value is 0 and the maximum value is 63.
This specifies the number of times Ingress LSR should transmit the LSP Self Ping packet. The default value is 3. The minimum value is 1 and the maximum value is 2^32-1.
This is the time interval (in milliseconds) between two LSP Self Ping packet re-transmissions. The default value is 1000. The minimum value is 1000 and the maximum value is 30000.
If set to True, RSVP Egress forwards the LSP Self Ping packet to Ingress LSR.
This specifies the amount by which the IP header's TTL value is decremented, before forwarding LSP Self Ping Packet to Ingress LSR.

If set to True, Egress LSR keeps the IP header DSCP value of the forwarded LSP self ping packet as it is. If set to False, Egress LSR overwrites the IP header DSCP value with the value configured in LSP Self Ping IP DSCP field, before forwarding self ping packet to Ingress LSR.

This specifies the value to be set in the IP header DSCP field of the forwarded Self Ping packet (when Retain LSP Self Ping DSCP is not selected). The default value is 48. The minimum value is 0 and the maximum value is 63.
This specifies the number of times Egress LSR drops the Self Ping packet. The default value is 0.
